Drive Like a Girl

Why we should look to women when it comes to stayin' alive on the roads Photo by Jenny Ueberberg on Unsplash

Data Overview

In this analysis, we will be taking a look at Australian road fatalities from 1989 to 2021. It includes road-related fatalities of drivers, passengers, pedestrians, motorcyclists and cyclists. There are around 52,000 records in the dataset.

You probably have some idea about what these statistics look like based on the various stories shared on mainstream media, but let's see if we can find anything interesting. So, hop in, put your seatbelt on, and let's go for a ride! :D

Introduction

The World Heath Organisation reports that approximately 1.3 million lives are cut short across the globe each year as a result of road traffic accidents. It's no wonder Australia takes road safety so seriously. We often see road safety ads and hear about Level Crossing Removal projects on TV. And we're ahead of most of the world when it comes to vehicle safety requirements and vehicle restrictions for inexperienced drivers. It seems like everything is being done to help reduce the danger on our roads, but how are we going when it comes to being safer drivers ourselves? Until fully autonomous cars become widely available, we remain in full control and take full responsibility for what happens when we drive.

Where We're Going Wrong

Young adults are the most likely fatalities on our roads. From the age of 15, the deaths begin to increase rapidly, peaking at age 18, the age at which many people obtain a provisional driver's license and are granted extra freedoms by their parents. And the deaths remain quite high for people in their 20s, although it decreases as they age. The number of fatalities appears to plateau at around age 60.

While it's no secret that young people carry the most risk on our roads, this spike in deaths is still quite shocking when you visualise it. I'm sure most of us have done something silly when we were young. The only difference is that we got away with it.

Let's take a closer look into where these fatalities are coming from.

Road User
Driver 23779
Passenger 12190
Pedestrian 8221
Motorcycle rider 6626
Pedal cyclist 1421
Motorcycle pillion passenger 361

Fatalities peak at around age 20 for all types of road users. Not only are drivers extremely risky in their early years, but so are motorcycle riders and cyclists.

Passenger deaths appear to spike with driver deaths. This may be caused by all the things people do when they get their license and their first car, such as driving their friends who don't yet have a license, or simply taking them for a spin in their new set of wheels. The rapid decline in passenger deaths as opposed to the slower decline of driver deaths could indicate that as they get older, many drivers were the sole occupant of their vehicle when the fatal accident occurred.

Pedestrians don't seem to be as lucky as the rest. The spike of deaths at young adulthood is accompanied by another spike in the late 70s. Perhaps it's worth taking the time to help that old lady cross the road.

When We're Going Wrong

The deadlist time of day is mid to late afternoon. The number of fatalities is highest from 3:00pm to 4:00pm, which could be explained by the end of the school day. The afternoon peak from 4:00pm to 6:00pm also claims a lot of lives. People rushing home from work after a tiring day of work is likely to be one of the reasons why the afternoon is so much deadlier than the mornings. I'm sure you've experienced the Afternoon Slump before. Don't forget to bring some snacks to recharge!

It's surprising to see how the number of deaths in the early morning compares with those in the middle of the day. Despite the roads being virtually empty at 4:00am, the number of deaths recorded at that time are still around half of that at midday.

Pedestrians and cyclists are most at risk during the morning and afternoon rush hours. The fatalities of all other road users experience a sharp peak in the middle of the afternoon, except for drivers whose fatalties are more evenly spread out. Their relatively higher death rate in the early hours is likely to be the reason why the overall deaths during those times are disproportionately higher.

While more drivers are killed during the day time, the majority of those accidents involved multiple vehicles. Single vehicle accidents are around twice as common than multiple vehicle accidents during the darker hours of the day (7:00pm to 5:00am).

Who's The Most Dangerous?

Multiple vehicle accidents can cause the death of drivers who were doing the right thing. Sometimes, you don't expect someone to speed through a red light and T-bone you or drift onto your side of the road on a dark night in the country.

In contrast, single vehicle accidents are almost always a result of driver fault and is therefore a better indicator of who the safer drivers are.

Time of day Gender
Day Male 4170
Female 1514
Night Male 5720
Female 974

Males are the more dangerous drivers by far. They make up 73% of day time fatalities and a whopping 85% of night time fatalities!

The interesting thing is that male and female drivers experience the most fatalities at different times of the day. Male deaths peak around midnight while female deaths peak around lunch time.

Recording higher deaths in the middle of the day isn't so surprising since more people drive during that time. So something must be happening in the middle of the night for so many men to lose their lives behind the wheel. Street racing, dingoes, aliens? Who knows?

It's not looking good for men involved in multiple vehicle accidents either. They record over double the number of fatalities in that category compared to women.

But while female fatalities in single and multiple vehicle accidents are practically even, around 33% more males are killed in single vehicle accidents compared to multiple vehicle accidents.

The distribution of multiple vehicle fatalities between males and females looks quite similar with deaths peaking in the middle of the afternoon and decline towards the end of the day. Men record twice as many multiple vehicle deaths as women during the day, but the difference is even larger during the night.

Time of day Gender
Day Male 5237
Female 2609
Night Male 2782
Female 773

What Makes Them Dangerous?

The difference in deaths between male and female drivers is a lot closer in multiple vehicle accidents than single vehicle accidents, but males are still more dangerous.

Apart from hooning and doing stunts at night, male driving behaviour is more dangerous in general. A report by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) shows that males regularly engage in more risky driving practices such as not wearing a seatbelt, driving under the influence of alcohol and speeding. Crashes involving male drivers were often more severe than those involving females.

Men were also found to be more aggressive drivers. Behaviour such as tailgaiting, changing lanes dangerously and displaying aggressive and rude behaviour to other road users was more common in males than females. Additionally, younger drivers were found to be more aggressive than older drivers in general.

Men were also found to be 3.4 times more likely than women to be ticketed for reckless driving, according to a study conducted by research firm Quality Planning.

It's no wonder why car insurance costs more for men.

Photo from Eclipse Driving School

So what makes a driver safe? Let's take a quick look at the behavioural differences in males and females.

If we go back thousands and thousands of years, qualities that enabled males to survive involved aggressive behaviour and risk-taking. Females on the other hand did not require these qualities. They were more concerned about caring for and protecting people around them - their children in particular.

Here are some key behavioural traits for males and females

Males Females
Dominant Sociable
Assertive Sensitive
Risk-prone Warm
Thrill-seeking Compassionate
Tough-minded Polite
Emotionally stable Anxious
Utilitarian Self-doubting

These qualities are reflected in driving behaviour, and unfortunately it makes men more dangerous behind the wheel.

Evolutionary behaviour isn't something that's easy to control. It's not easy to change something that's been programmed into us, but if we know what we need to do and we're more conscious about our actions, that can certainly help.

So guys, do us all a favour and drive like a girl!

Jake Nelson, the director of the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety agrees:
"Driving aggressively isnt worth the risk. When you get behind the wheel, be patient, be kind, and obey traffic laws so everyone gets home safely."

It's Not All Bad

Despite all that, we're actually doing very well when it comes to stayin' alive!

The mortality rate has been decreasing fairly consistently since 1989. We've gone down from 16 deaths per 100,000 to just three! With safer cars and more safety measures being put into place, we should only expect this to decline even more.

The gap between males and females has been closing over time. In the early to mid 2000s, the male mortality rate was nearly 3 times that of females. Now it's closer to 2 times.

A big improvement can also be seen from our younger road users. The mortality rate of people aged 0 to 39 has decreased much more than those aged 40+. Given that the majority of road fatalities are younger people, this is great news!

Conclusion

In the past 33 years, we have lost 52,000 lives on Australian roads. Drivers are our most common fatalities with young, inexperienced drivers in early adulthood being the riskiest by far. Fortunately, as people grow older and gain more experience, the number of driver deaths declines, but the same can't be said for pedestrians whose deaths begin to increase again at around age 60. So it's important for us to look out for our older road users.

We also need to take a different approach to driving depending on the time of day. The morning and afternoon rush hours are the most dangerous for cyclists, and the afternoons are particularly dangerous for drivers and pedestrians. We've seen that the majority of driver deaths during the day are caused by multiple-vehicle accidents while an even greater majority of driver deaths at night are a result of single-vehicle accidents. During the day, drivers should look out for other road users. During the night, they should look out for themselves.

Additionally, we have seen a significantly higher number of male fatalities compared to female fatalities. Men are found to be hard-wired differently to women, which results in more aggressive and risky driving behaviour, leading to a greater chance of having an accident. This makes women the safer drivers, so it wouldn't hurt for everyone to drive like a girl.
